      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "This answer alludes the reader that the result will always be positive, but consider <code>int n = Integer.MAX_VALUE</code> and now try <code>((1 % n) + n) % n</code> The overflow results in <code>-1 % n</code> = -1.  Where you expect <code>1 + n % n</code> = 1.  Also--distinguishing between a remainder and a modulus class in this way is a bit misleading. A remainder is equal to the smallest element of the modulus class. The difference is that Python does normal <i>moding</i> where <code>5 =&gt; {[0], [1], [2], [3], [4]}</code> where Java does symmetric moding <code>5 =&gt; {[-2], [-1], [0], [1], [2]}</code>."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 15931,
      "reputation" : 14582,
      "user_id" : 34201,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a6608f328e842fcd81e75fb6e7edef5b?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "andrewmu",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/34201/andrewmu"
    },
    "is_accepted" : true,
    "score" : 213,
    "last_activity_date" : 1432289025,
    "last_edit_date" : 1495540502,
    "creation_date" : 1300750950,
    "answer_id" : 5385053,
    "question_id" : 5385024,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>The problem here is that in Python the % operator returns the <strong>modulus</strong> and in Java it returns the <strong>remainder</strong>.  These functions give the same values for positive arguments, but the modulus always returns positive results for negative input, whereas the remainder may give negative results.  There's some more information about it in <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/13683563/whats-the-difference-between-mod-and-remainder\">this question</a>.</p>\n\n<p>You can find the positive value by doing this:</p>\n\n<pre><code>int i = (((-1 % 2) + 2) % 2)\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>or this:</p>\n\n<pre><code>int i = -1 % 2;\nif (i&lt;0) i += 2;\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>(obviously -1 or 2 can be whatever you want the numerator or denominator to be)</p>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 186889,
        "reputation" : 1781,
        "user_id" : 424555,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/04dbacca1652c7f03fc837cd43109b9d?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
        "display_name" : "Cachapa",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/424555/cachapa"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1355665354,
      "post_id" : 5385091,
      "comment_id" : 19156244,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "This expression didn&#39;t work for me. For negative values I was getting values between 1:m instead of the expected 0:m-1, as in the case where n is positive. The solution from andrewmu functioned as expected."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 278210,
      "reputation" : 178895,
      "user_id" : 572670,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 92,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5011cf6d98e276b1bdc2cb321546e528?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "amit",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/572670/amit"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1355665676,
    "last_edit_date" : 1355665676,
    "creation_date" : 1300751411,
    "answer_id" : 5385091,
    "question_id" : 5385024,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>If you need <code>n % m</code> then:</p>\n\n<pre><code>int i = (n &lt; 0) ? (m - (abs(n) % m) ) %m : (n % m);\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>mathematical explanation:</p>\n\n<pre><code>n = -1 * abs(n)\n-&gt; n % m = (-1 * abs(n) ) % m\n-&gt; (-1 * (abs(n) % m) ) % m\n-&gt; m - (abs(n) % m))\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 61276,
      "reputation" : 55517,
      "user_id" : 182705,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/441ab3bb45522c8049d12f3aed6789ef?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Neil",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/182705/neil"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1300752956,
    "creation_date" : 1300752956,
    "answer_id" : 5385277,
    "question_id" : 5385024,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>If the modulus is a power of 2 then you can use a bitmask:</p>\n\n<pre><code>int i = -1 &amp; ~-2; // -1 MOD 2 is 1\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>By comparison the Pascal language provides two operators; REM takes the sign of the numerator (<code>x REM y</code> is <code>x - (x DIV y) * y</code> where <code>x DIV y</code> is <code>TRUNC(x / y)</code>) and MOD requires a positive denominator and returns a positive result.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 12677725,
        "reputation" : 1275,
        "user_id" : 9212745,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/61f09e6b736d6620d2de52cd9dcbef28?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
        "display_name" : "rdxdkr",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/9212745/rdxdkr"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1713122130,
      "post_id" : 31140209,
      "comment_id" : 138084854,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "Splendid answer, of course you can then call <code>Math.abs()</code> on the output of <code>Math.floorMod()</code> to guarantee that the result is always non negative."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 2674955,
      "reputation" : 10671,
      "user_id" : 2311557,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 61,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/KOoOQ.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "codepleb",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2311557/codepleb"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 159,
    "last_activity_date" : 1485964483,
    "last_edit_date" : 1495542884,
    "creation_date" : 1435672382,
    "answer_id" : 31140209,
    "question_id" : 5385024,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p><strong>Since Java 8</strong> you can use the <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/Math.html#floorMod-int-int-\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Math.floorMod()</a> method:</p>\n\n<pre><code>Math.floorMod(-1, 2); //== 1\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Note: If the modulo-value (here <code>2</code>) is negative, all output values will be negative too. :)</p>\n\n<p>Source: <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/a/25830153/2311557\">https://stackoverflow.com/a/25830153/2311557</a></p>\n"
  }, {
